ce as “the most Dangerous Enemies America knows” and ordered Pennsylvania and Delaware to apprehend them. In response, Keystone State officials sent twenty men—seventeen of whom were Quakers—into exile, banishing them to Virginia, where they were held for a year.Prisoners of Congress reconstructs this moment in American history through the experiences of four families: the Drinkers, the Fishers, the Pembertons, and the Gilpins. Identifying them as the new nation’s first political prisoners, Norman E. Donoghue II relates how the Quakers, once the preeminent power in Pennsylvania and an integral constituency of the colonies and early republic, came to be reviled by patriots who saw refusal to fight the English as borderline sedition. Surprising, vital, and vividly told, this narrative of political and literal warfare waged by the United States against a pacifist religious group during the Revolutionary War era sheds new light on an essential aspect of American history. It will appeal to anyone interested in learning more about the nation’s founding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aExileszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy18th century. 0aExileszVirginiazWinchesterxHistoryy18th century. 0aSociety of FriendszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy18th century. 0aSociety of FriendszVirginiazWinchesterxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAmerican Crisis by Thomas Paine.  aBanishing Law.  aElizabeth Sandwith Drinker.  aEpistle to the Quakers” in Common Sense.  aFriends meeting houses.  aGilpin.  aHenry Drinker (1734-1809).  aIsrael Pemberton.  aJames Pemberton.  aJohn Pemberton.  aPhiladelphia Yearly Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends.  aQuaker exile.  aSarah Logan Fisher.  aThomas Paine.  aloyalty oaths or the T